params.text:
As this is a demo demonstrating PyKEEN's ability with temporal graphs, we have to import a custom dataset containing `head`, `relation`, `tail` columns.

We also expect that the data recieved by PyKEEN specific boxes will contain `head`, `relation` and `tail` named columns, as long as the dataset is in this format everything will run smoothly. When talking about `triples` in this demo we mean a tuple of `(head, relation, tail)`

As this graph is very large, we will only sample 1% of it for demonstration purposes, removing this we can take full advantage of PyKEEN's ablility to work on very large graphs too (as long as we have computational power).

These boxes are our train/test/validation split.

In this demo the split is based on timestamp. In the example every edge before `2011` is in the training set, and after `2010` 70% of the edges are in the testing set and 30% are in the validation set.

params.text:
## Model definition
Here we can define the PyKEEN model that we would like to use in downstream tasks.

We need to choose what kind of model we would want, and what will the final embedding dimension of the model be, and the backend will take care of the rest.

## Model training
This is where the magic happens. In this box the selected model will try to learn the graph structure which we can later reuse as embeddings, or do link-prediction.

You have your training/testing/validation parameters, your optimizer, what kind of loss function should the model use, and for how many epochs should the training run.

But so far our dataset only contained positive triples (that are in the graph) but for training we will need negative triples also. In an `Open World Assumption` (OWA) all triples not part of the graph will be considered unknown (neither positive nor negative) this will lead to over-fitting. In the opposite setting `Closed World Assumption` (CWA) every triple not part of the graph will be considered negative, this leads to under-fitting. So in PyKEEN we have two other approaches:
The training approach will generate negative triples for us like so:
- `LCWA` (Local Closed World Assumption): Where a particular subset of triples (generated with specific generators) that are not part of the knowledge graph are considered as negative.
- `sLCWA` (Stochastic `LCWA`): Where a random subset of the union of the head and tail generation strategies from `LCWA` are considered as negative triples. There are a few benefits from doing this:
  1. Reduce computational workload
  2. Spare updates (i.e., only a few rows of the embedding are affected)
   3. Ability to integrate new negative sampling strategies

The training uses early stopping which is currently not configurable yet, but it has a frequency of `5` epochs with a patience of `40`. It tracks `adjusted hits@k`, with a relative delta of `0.05%` over `200` epochs.

Model training performance graphs. Loss is the same as in traditional PyTorch models.

Early stopping tracks every `frequency` epochs the models performance on the `validation` set. The metric is the previously mentioned `adjusted hits@k`. X-axis is every evaluation and **not** epoch.

### Triple prediction
For this, we need to give a table of triples, and all of those triples will be scored by the chosen model.

## Predictions / Inference
After training, the model can assign a score to an arbitrary triple, whether it appeared during training, testing, or not. In PyKEEN, each is implemented such that the higher the score (or less negative the score), the more likely a triple is to be true.

However, for most models, these scores do not have obvious statistical interpretations. This has two main consequences:
- The score for a triple from one model can not be compared to the score for that triple from another model
- There is no *a priori* minimum score for a triple to be labeled as true, so predictions must be given as a prioritization by sorting a set of triples by their respective scores.

In PyKEEN we have 3 different options for prediction.

### Target prediction
For this prediction we need to give 2 out of the 3 possible options from `head`, `relation`, `tail`. The missing one will be predicted. PyKEEN will forward all possible combinations of the missing value and score them all with the chosen model.

### Full prediction
For this PyKEEN will find all possible combinations of all entities and relations and score them all. 

Notice that this operation can be prohibitively expensive for reasonably sized knowledge graphs, and the model may produce additional ill-calibrated scores for entity/relation combinations it has never seen paired before during training.

In addition to the expensive calculations, this additionally requires us to have sufficient memory available to store all scores. A computationally equally expensive option with reduced, fixed memory requirement is to store only the triples with the top `k` scores. This can be done through the optional parameter `k`.
This is for checking that there are enough timestamps for all timestamps (if we are sampling)

## Model evaluation
Knowledge graph embedding are usually evaluated on the task of link prediction. To this end, an evaluation set of triples is provided, and for each triple in this set, two tasks are solved:
- **Right-Side** In the right-side prediction task, a pair of head entity and relation are given and aim to predict the tail
- **Left-Side** Analogously, in the left-side prediction task, a pair of relation and tail entity are provided and aim to predict the head

### Rank-based evaluator
In the rank-based evaluation protocol, the scores are used to sort the list of possible choices by decreasing score, and determine the rank of the true choice, i.e. the index in the sorted list. Smaller ranks indicate better performance. Based on these individual ranks, which are obtained for each evaluation triple and each side of the prediction (left/right), there exist several aggregation measures to quantify the performance of a model in a single number.

Most models in PyKEEN are built from the following:
- an interaction, which is used to score triples
- entity and relation representations (which are usually embeddings)

Right now these are not customizable as we are initializing a top-level model with default parameters. Usually these are the best performing, taken from the paper they were defined in.

PyKEEN does support hyper-parameter optimization, but that is not yet implemented in LynxKite.

### Macro rank-based evaluator
Real graphs often are scale-free, i.e., there are a few nodes / entities which have a high degree, often called hub, while the majority of nodes has only a few neighbors. This also impacts the evaluation triples: since the hub nodes occur in a large number of triples, they are also more likely to be part of evaluation triples. Thus, performing well on triples containing hub entities contributes strongly to the overall performance.

There are arguments that we want these entities to have a strong effect on evaluation: since they occur often, they are seemingly important, and thus evaluation should reflect that. However, sometimes we also do not want to have this effect, but rather measure the performance evenly across nodes. PyKEEN implements this evaluator, which ensures that triples are weighted such that each unique ranking task, e.g., a (head, relation)-pair for tail prediction, contributes evenly.

## Classification evaluator
This evaluator implements most of the classification metrics found in classification tasks i.e. `accuracy`, `precision`, `F1 score`.

## Filtering
The rank-based evaluation allows using the “filtered setting”, which is enabled by default. When evaluating the tail prediction for a triple `(h,r,t)`, i.e. scoring all triples `(h,r,e)`, there may be additional known triples `(h,r,t')` for `t' != t`. If the model predicts a higher score for `(h,r,t')`, the rank will increase, and hence the measured model performance will decrease. However, giving `(h,r,t')` a high score (and thus a low rank) is desirable since it is a true triple as well. Thus, the filtered evaluation setting ignores for a given triple `(h,r,t)` the scores of all other *known* true triples `(h,r,t')`.
